<section id="headline">
    <h1>&lt;h1&gt;</h1>
    <p>Headline text scales with the page size, stopping when it's big enough.</p>
    <aside>
      <p>Headlines can be targeted with the <code>.headline-elements({})</code> ruleset mixin.</p>
    </aside>
    <h1>Man bites dog (h1)</h1>
    <h2>Man bites dog (h2)</h2>
    <h3>Man bites dog (h3)</h3>
    <h4>Man bites dog (h4)</h4>
    <h5>Man bites dog (h5)</h5>
    <h6>Man bites dog (h6)</h6>
    <p>Headlines scale proportionally with the page, up until they get big enough and stop.</p>
</section>

<section id="form">
    <h1>&lt;form&gt;</h1>

    <p>Strapless has simple form support:</p>
    <form>
        <h3>Enter your information</h3>
        <label>First name:</label>
        <input type="text" name="firstname">
        <label>Last name:</label>
        <input type="text" name="lastname">
        <label>Textarea:</label>
        <textarea rows="4"></textarea>
        <footer>
            <button onclick="return false" class="reaction">Submit</button>
            <button onclick="return false">Cancel</button>
        </footer>
    </form>

    <pre>&lt;form&gt;
    &lt;h3&gt;Enter your information&lt;/h3&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;First name:&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="firstname"&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;Last name:&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" name="lastname"&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;Textarea:&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;textarea rows="4"&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;
    &lt;footer class="action"&gt;
        &lt;button&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;button&gt;Cancel&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/footer&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</pre>
</section>

<section id="blockquotes">
    <h1>&lt;blockquote&gt;</h1>
    <blockquote>
        You may delay, but time will not.
        <cite>Benjamin Franklin</cite>
    </blockquote>
    <pre>&lt;blockquote&gt;
    You may delay, but time will not.
    &lt;cite&gt;Benjamin Franklin&lt;/cite&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;</pre>
    <br>
    <p>They alternate switching sides by default.</p>
    <blockquote class="reaction">
        Blushing is the color of virtue.
        <cite>Diogenes</cite>
    </blockquote>
</section>

